---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeTabs from '../../components/CodeTabs.astro';

const repo = 'https://github.com/MANVENDRA-github/Jolt-UI';

const scaffoldTabs = [
  {
    label: 'bash',
    lang: 'bash',
    code: `# 1. describe the component once in scripts/contracts/<id>.mjs
# 2. stamp the whole slice (schema + 3 skins + demo + tests + registry + parity):
node scripts/gen-component.mjs <id>
# 3. customize the animation test-first, then run the gates:
pnpm verify && pnpm test:cli && pnpm test:e2e`,
  },
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Contributing — Jolt UI"
  description="How Jolt UI is built: one design language across three frameworks, the gen-component scaffolder, test-first, and the parity gate."
>
  <h1>Contributing</h1>
  <p>
    Jolt UI is one design language shipped as three framework skins. Contributions keep that
    promise: a component must look, move, and behave identically across React, Vue, and Svelte,
    proven by an automated parity gate.
  </p>

  <h2>One design language, three skins</h2>
  <p>
    The look lives in <code>@jolt/tokens</code> and the behavior + API (Zod prop schemas, animation logic)
    in <code>@jolt/core</code>; each framework package is a thin skin over that core. A skin may
    only differ in idiomatic lifecycle glue — never in look, motion, or props. If you find yourself
    reimplementing animation logic per framework, lift it into the core instead.
  </p>

  <h2>Add a component</h2>
  <p>
    CSS components are generated from a single declarative <strong>contract</strong> by the
    <code>gen-component</code> scaffolder — it stamps the schema, all three skins, the demo page, the
    unit tests, the registry entries, and the parity cells, emitting a working component you then customize.
    GSAP components are hand-written following the same slice.
  </p>
  <CodeTabs tabs={scaffoldTabs} />

  <h2>Test-first, and the gates</h2>
  <p>
    Every change is test-first: write a failing test that captures the behavior, then make it pass.
    Three gates must stay green:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>pnpm verify</code> — typecheck, lint, unit tests, and the registry-sync check.</li>
    <li>
      <code>pnpm test:cli</code> — installs the component into a throwaway project and type-checks it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>pnpm test:e2e</code> — the <strong>parity gate</strong>: renders every component in all
      three frameworks and asserts they're identical.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Pull requests</h2>
  <p>
    One focused, reviewable PR per change, with a conventional-commit title. Always branch → PR →
    merge (never push to <code>main</code>), and a component must exist in all three frameworks and
    pass parity before it ships. The full checklist lives in
    <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/COMPONENT_GUIDE.md`}>COMPONENT_GUIDE.md</a> in the repo.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
